    "created_at": "2017-08-13T16:38:56Z",
    "updated_at": "2017-08-13T16:38:56Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "> I don't think this is a good idea at all. Why are you not simply converting these 1-tuples?\r\n\r\nFor the categorical case, we need to treat `categories=[1, 2, 3]` differently than `categories=[(1,), (2,), (3,)]`. I could add additional code there to special case categories of length 1, but the fix here is much cleaner.\r\n\r\n> This is just adding complexity.\r\n\r\nPerhaps a bit? I'm not sure an additional keyword + a one line change to the MI constructor is a maintenance burden.\r\n\r\nWe've been trying to remove all the areas where the return type is dependent on the values, like it is here. That said, I don't think this is worth breaking API over, since it's been this way for so long. It's the mirror behavior of `Index` with tuples:\r\n\r\n```python\r\nIn [9]: pd.Index([(1, 2), (3, 4)])\r\nOut[9]:\r\nMultiIndex(levels=[[1, 3], [2, 4]],\r\n           labels=[[0, 1], [0, 1]])\r\n\r\nIn [10]: pd.Index([(1, 2), (3, 4)], tupleize_cols=False)\r\nOut[10]: Index([(1, 2), (3, 4)], dtype='object')\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe constructors try to be smart about what you want, but give you control if you know better what you want."
  },
